{{about|the former auberge in Valletta|the one in Birgu|Auberge d'Allemagne, Birgu}} {{use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} {{use list-defined references|date=February 2014}} {{Use British English|date=February 2014}} {{Infobox building | name = Auberge d'Allemagne | native_name = Berġa ta' Alemanja | native_name_lang = mt | image = Auberge d'Alemagne.jpg | image_caption = Laying of the foundation stone of [[St Paul's Pro-Cathedral]] on 20 May 1839, with the remains of the auberge in the background | coordinates = {{coord|35|54|2|N|14|30|43|E|display=inline,title}} | status = Destroyed | building_type = Auberge | architectural_style = [[Mannerism (architecture)|Mannerist]] | location = [[Valletta]], [[Malta]] | start_date = 1571 | completion_date = 1575 | demolition_date = 1839 | material = [[Limestone]] | architect = [[Girolamo Cassar]] }}
'''Auberge d'Allemagne''' ({{lang-mt|Berġa ta' Alemanja}}) was an auberge in [[Valletta]], [[Malta]]. It was built between 1571 and 1575<ref>{{cite web|title=Auberges in Valletta|url=https://vassallohistory.wordpress.com/auberges-in-malta/|website=vassallohistory.wordpress.com|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> to house knights of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] from the [[Langue (Knights Hospitaller)|langue]] of [[Holy Roman Empire|Germany]].
It was vacated in 1798 when the Order was expelled during the [[French occupation of Malta]]. By the 1830s, the building was used as the residence of the Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacGill|first1=Thomas|title=A hand book, or guide, for strangers visiting Malta|date=1839|publisher=Luigi Tonna|location=[[Malta]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fm4DAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=63}}</ref> It was demolished in 1839 to make way for [[St Paul's Pro-Cathedral]].<ref name=angelfire>{{cite web|title=the auberges in valletta|url=http://www.angelfire.com/ma/maltarchitecture/auberges_valletta.html|website=angelfire.com|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Auberge d'Allemagne was the only auberge in Malta to be intentionally demolished, since the other destroyed auberges were pulled down due to damage sustained in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The houses of the Knights of St. John|url=http://www.malta.com/en/attraction/culture/building-fortification/the-auberges|website=malta.com|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Some remains may still exist in situ.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Raymomd|last=Scicluna|journal=Annual Report 2016 Superintendence of Cultural Heritage|title=Dokument imqiegħed fuq il-Mejda tal-Kamra tad-Deputati fis-Seduta|volume=It-Tnax-Il Legislatura|issue=Numru 501|date=3 April 2017|publisher=Ministru għall-Ġustizzja, Kultura u Gvern Lokali|language=Maltese|url=https://www.parlament.mt/media/88791/08699.pdf|page=25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916192403/https://www.parlament.mt/media/88791/08699.pdf|archive-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Malta Valletta BW 2011-10-07 12-32-05.JPG|thumb|left|The site of the auberge is now occupied by [[St Paul's Pro-Cathedral]]]] The auberge was designed by the Maltese architect [[Girolamo Cassar]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schiavone|first1=Michael J.|title=Dictionary of Maltese Biographies Vol. 1 A-F|date=2009|publisher=Pubblikazzjonijiet Indipendenza|location=[[Pietà, Malta|Pietà]]|isbn=9789993291329|pages=520–521}}</ref> but almost nothing is known about the structure.<ref name=angelfire/>
==Further reading== *[http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Archivio%20storico%20di%20Malta/ASM.04(1933)2-4(Apr.-Dic.)/01%20L'Albergia%20della%20Lingua%20d'Alemagna.pdf L'Albergia della Lingua d'Alemagna / G. Darmanin Demajo. ASM. 4(1934)2-4(Apr.-Dic.65-96)]
