'''Cannabis in Gibraltar''' is illegal, but due to its proximity to North Africa and to mainland Europe, Gibraltar has frequently been used for cannabis trafficking.

==Trafficking==
Prior to 1957, cannabis trafficking in Gibraltar was limited to small personal amounts by tourists, but with the arrival of the [[Hippie Trail]], larger amounts began to be commercially smuggled, leading Gibraltar to become one of the main entry points to Europe for Moroccan hashish.<ref name="Booth2015">{{cite book|author=Martin Booth|title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecITBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA282|date=16 June 2015|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-08219-0|pages=282–{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}<!--Terminal page number needed.-->}}</ref> In the mid-1990s the market began to shift, with decreasing focus on trafficking cannabis and illegal cigarettes, and more on trafficking heroin and cocaine.<ref name="Gold2004">{{cite book|author=Peter Gold|title=Gibraltar: British or Spanish?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6ZnmbCBJtkC&pg=PT187|date=2 August 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-27674-5|pages=187–{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}<!--Terminal page number needed.-->}}</ref>

==Medical cannabis==
In 2017, Gibraltar legalized [[Sativex]] oral spray to treat Multiple Sclerosis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.gi/2017/02/green-light-for-cannabis-based-ms-medicine/|title=Green light for cannabis-based MS medicine – Gibraltar Chronicle|website=chronicle.gi}}</ref>

