[[File:Lisbon Mosque.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The [[Lisbon Mosque]].]]
{{Islam by country}}
According to the [[Instituto Nacional de Estatística]] (the National [[Statistics|Statistical]] Institute of [[Portugal]]), there were, according to the 1991 [[census]], 9,134 [[Islam|Muslims]] in Portugal, about 0.1% of the total population, even though the Islamic Community of Lisbon presently points to a number of about 40,000 according to 2011 estimates.<ref>[http://www.comunidadeislamica.pt/02b.php?nivel_1=2&nivel_2=22 Comunidade Islâmica de Lisboa - Comunidade Islâmica em Portugal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218031757/http://www.comunidadeislamica.pt/02b.php?nivel_1=2&nivel_2=22 |date=2009-12-18 }} and [http://www.comunidadeislamica.pt/02b3.php?nivel_1=2&nivel_2=22&nivel_3=223 Comunidade Islâmica de Lisboa - Quantos somos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218034946/http://www.comunidadeislamica.pt/02b3.php?nivel_1=2&nivel_2=22&nivel_3=223 |date=2009-12-18 }} (dead links) (in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]])</ref> The majority of Muslims in the country are [[Sunni]]s, followed by approximately 5,000 to 7,000 [[Sevener|Sevener Ismā'īlī Shīʻa]] Muslims. There is also a small number of [[Ahmadiyya]] Muslims.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mamiop8TPxYC&pg=PA193&dq&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YdmiU_yQPNH07AaJroG4Ag&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Islam, Europe's Second Religion: The New Social, Cultural, and Political Landscapes | page=193 | author=Shireen Hunter | publisher=Praeger Publishers | isbn=0-275-97608-4 | accessdate=19 June 2014}}</ref> Most of the Muslim population originates from the former [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese overseas provinces]] of [[Guinea-Bissau]] and [[Mozambique]], most of the latter having their origin in [[South Asia]].

==History==
[[File:Itin mertola.jpg|right|thumb|Old Mosque in [[Mértola]]. Converted into a church]]
From 711 to 1249, much of the territory of what is now Portugal (namely south of the [[Mondego River|Mondego]] river, but particularly in the [[Alentejo]] and the [[Algarve]]) was under [[Moors|Muslim]] control, and was called [[Gharb Al-Andalus|Gharb Al-Andalus]] (the west of [[Al-Andalus]]). This presence has left some [[Culture of Portugal|cultural]] [[cultural heritage|heritage]] in Portugal, such as [[Islamic art]]. The town of [[Mértola]], in the [[Alentejo]], possesses the only partial remains of a mosque, converted to a [[Catholic church]] after the ''[[Reconquista]]''.

